<?xml version='1.0' encoding='utf-8'?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-logistic-regression" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Logistic Regression</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      This chapter introduces two related topics: log odds and logistic regression.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-log-odds">
    <title>Log Odds</title>

    <p>
      When I was in grad school, I signed up for a class on the Theory of Knowledge.
      In the first lecture, the professor said something like, "Everything you believe,
      you believe with some probability. For some things, like 'my name is Professor So-and-So',
      the probability is high. For others, like 'life exists on other planets', the probability
      might be 50-50."
    </p>
    <p>
      I can use this anecdote to demonstrate Bayes's Rule on a logarithmic scale and show
      why log odds are useful.
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a function that converts odds to probability.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
def prob(o):
    return o / (o+1)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The following table shows the odds after each update, the corresponding probabilities,
      and the differences between successive probabilities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
import pandas as pd

index = ['prior', '1 student', '2 students', '3 students']

table = pd.DataFrame(index=index)
table['odds'] = [10, 10/3, 10/9, 10/27]
table['prob'] = prob(table['odds'])
table['prob diff'] = table['prob'].diff() * 100
table.fillna('--')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Each update uses the same likelihood, but the changes in probability are not the same.
      Let's see what happens if we add a column for log odds.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
import numpy as np

table['log odds'] = np.log(table['odds'])
table['log odds diff'] = table['log odds'].diff()
table.fillna('--')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      You might notice that the log odds change by the same amount with each update.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
np.log(1/3)
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-space-shuttle">
    <title>The Space Shuttle Problem</title>

    <p>
      As an example of logistic regression, I'll solve a problem related to the Space Shuttle
      Challenger disaster. The following cell downloads the data.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
download('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/CamDavidsonPilon/Probabilistic-Programming-and-Bayesian-Methods-for-Hackers/master/Chapter2_MorePyMC/data/challenger_data.csv')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      I'll read the data and do some cleaning.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
data = pd.read_csv('challenger_data.csv', parse_dates=[0])

# avoiding column names with spaces
data.rename(columns={'Damage Incident': 'Damage'}, inplace=True)

# dropping row 3, in which Damage Incident is NaN,
# and row 24, which is the record for the Challenger
data.drop(labels=[3, 24], inplace=True)

# convert the Damage column to integer
data['Damage'] = data['Damage'].astype(int)

data
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here are the first few rows:
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
data.head()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here are the number of launches and damage incidents.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
len(data), data['Damage'].sum()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The following figure shows the relationship between damage and temperature.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from utils import decorate

def plot_data(data):
    """Plot damage as a function of temperature.
    
    data: DataFrame
    """
    plt.plot(data['Temperature'], data['Damage'], 'o', 
             label='data', color='C0', alpha=0.4)

    decorate(ylabel="Probability of damage",
         xlabel="Outside temperature (deg F)",
         title="Damage to O-Rings vs Temperature")
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
plot_data(data)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      I'll center the data around the mean temperature.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
offset = data['Temperature'].mean().round()
data['x'] = data['Temperature'] - offset
offset
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      And for consistency I'll create a copy of the <c>Damage</c> column called <c>y</c>.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
data['y'] = data['Damage']
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Before doing a Bayesian update, I'll use <c>statsmodels</c> to run a conventional
      logistic regression to get the maximum likelihood estimates.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf

formula = 'y ~ x'
results = smf.logit(formula, data=data).fit(disp=False)
results.params
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      <c>results</c> contains a "point estimate" for each parameter.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
inter = results.params['Intercept']
slope = results.params['x']
xs = np.arange(53, 83) - offset
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      We can use the logistic regression equation to compute log odds:
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
log_odds = inter + slope * xs
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      And then convert to probabilities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
odds = np.exp(log_odds)
ps = odds / (odds + 1)
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
ps.mean()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Converting log odds to probabilities is a common enough operation that it has a name,
      the logistic function, or expit.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from scipy.special import expit

ps = expit(inter + slope * xs)
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
ps.mean()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here's what the logistic model looks like with these estimated parameters.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
plt.plot(xs+offset, ps, label='model', color='C1')

plot_data(data)
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-prior">
    <title>Prior Distribution</title>

    <p>
      I'll use uniform distributions for both parameters, using the results from
      <c>statsmodels</c> to choose the range.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from utils import make_uniform

qs = np.linspace(-5, 1, num=101)
prior_inter = make_uniform(qs, 'Intercept')
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
qs = np.linspace(-0.8, 0.1, num=101)
prior_slope = make_uniform(qs, 'Slope')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      We can use <c>make_joint</c> to construct the joint prior distribution.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from utils import make_joint

joint = make_joint(prior_inter, prior_slope)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      <c>joint_pmf</c> is a <c>Pmf</c> with two levels in the index, one for each parameter.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from empiricaldist import Pmf

joint_pmf = Pmf(joint.stack())
joint_pmf.head()
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-likelihood">
    <title>Likelihood</title>

    <p>
      To do the update, we have to compute the likelihood of the data for each pair
      of parameters.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
grouped = data.groupby('x')['y'].agg(['count', 'sum'])
grouped.head()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The result is a <c>DataFrame</c> with two columns: <c>count</c> is the number of
      launches at each temperature and <c>sum</c> is the number of damage incidents.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
ns = grouped['count']
ks = grouped['sum']
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      To compute the likelihood of the data, let's assume temporarily that the parameters
      are the values from <c>statsmodels</c>.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
xs = grouped.index
ps = expit(inter + slope * xs)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      <c>ps</c> contains the probability of damage for each launch temperature.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from scipy.stats import binom

likes = binom.pmf(ks, ns, ps)
likes
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Each element of <c>likes</c> is the probability of seeing <c>k</c> damage incidents
      in <c>n</c> launches with a given damage probability.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
likes.prod()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      That's how we compute the likelihood of the data for a particular pair of parameters.
      The following loop computes it for all pairs.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
likelihood = joint_pmf.copy()
for slope, inter in joint_pmf.index:
    ps = expit(inter + slope * xs)
    likes = binom.pmf(ks, ns, ps)
    likelihood[slope, inter] = likes.prod() 
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-update">
    <title>The Update</title>

    <p>
      Now we can compute the posterior distribution in the usual way.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
posterior_pmf = joint_pmf * likelihood
posterior_pmf.normalize()
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Because we used a uniform prior, the parameter pair with the highest likelihood
      also has the highest posterior probability.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
pd.Series(posterior_pmf.max_prob(),
          index=['slope', 'inter'])
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      So we can confirm that the results of the Bayesian update are consistent with
      the results of logistic regression.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
results.params
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      If we unstack the posterior <c>Pmf</c> we can make a contour plot of the joint posterior
      distribution.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from utils import plot_contour

joint_posterior = posterior_pmf.unstack()
plot_contour(joint_posterior)
decorate(title='Joint posterior distribution')
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-marginals">
    <title>Marginal Distributions</title>

    <p>
      Finally, we can extract the marginal distributions.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
from utils import marginal

marginal_inter = marginal(joint_posterior, 0)
marginal_slope = marginal(joint_posterior, 1)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here's the posterior distribution of <c>inter</c>.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>

marginal_inter.plot(label='intercept', color='C4')

decorate(xlabel='Intercept',
         ylabel='PDF',
         title='Posterior marginal distribution of intercept')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      And here's the posterior distribution of <c>slope</c>.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_slope.plot(label='slope', color='C2')

decorate(xlabel='Slope',
         ylabel='PDF',
         title='Posterior marginal distribution of slope')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here are the posterior means.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
pd.Series([marginal_inter.mean(), marginal_slope.mean()],
          index=['inter', 'slope'])
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
results.params
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-transforming">
    <title>Transforming Distributions</title>

    <p>
      Let's interpret these parameters. Recall that the intercept is the log odds of
      damage when temperature is at the offset (about 70 degrees F).
      So the probability of damage at 70 degrees is <c>expit(inter)</c>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Here is a function that transforms a <c>Pmf</c> by applying a function to its quantities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
def transform(pmf, func):
    """Transform the quantities in a Pmf."""
    ps = pmf.ps
    qs = func(pmf.qs)
    return Pmf(ps, qs, copy=True)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      If we call <c>transform</c> and pass <c>expit</c> as a parameter, it transforms the
      log odds to probabilities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_probs = transform(marginal_inter, expit)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      <c>Pmf</c> provides a <c>transform</c> method that does the same thing.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_probs = marginal_inter.transform(expit)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Here's the posterior distribution for the probability of damage at 70 degrees F.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_probs.plot(color='C1')

decorate(xlabel='Probability of damage at 70 deg F',
         ylabel='PDF',
         title='Posterior marginal distribution of probabilities')
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The mean of this distribution is about 22%, which is the probability of damage at 70 degrees.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
mean_prob = marginal_probs.mean()
mean_prob
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Now let's look more closely at the estimated slope. In the logistic model, the slope
      is the log of the likelihood ratio corresponding to a one degree increase in temperature.
      So the likelihood ratio is <c>exp(slope)</c>.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_lr = marginal_slope.transform(np.exp)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The result is the posterior distribution of likelihood ratios; here's what it looks like.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
marginal_lr.plot(color='C3')

decorate(xlabel='Likelihood ratio of 1 deg F',
         ylabel='PDF',
         title='Posterior marginal distribution of likelihood ratios')
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
mean_lr = marginal_lr.mean()
mean_lr
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      Notice that the posterior mean of the probability is not the same as the probability
      computed from the posterior mean of the parameter. The right way is to transform first,
      then compute the mean.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
expit(marginal_inter.mean()), marginal_probs.mean()
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
np.exp(marginal_slope.mean()), marginal_lr.mean()
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-predictive">
    <title>Predictive Distributions</title>

    <p>
      In the logistic model, the parameters are interpreted as the slope and intercept
      of a line in log-odds space. We can use the posterior distribution of these parameters
      to generate a predictive distribution of probabilities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
np.random.seed(17)
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
sample = posterior_pmf.choice(101)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The result is an array of 101 tuples, each representing a possible pair of parameters.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
sample.shape
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
sample.dtype
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
type(sample[0])
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      To generate predictions, I'll use a range of temperatures from 31 degrees F (the
      temperature on the morning of the Challenger launch) to 82 degrees.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
temps = np.arange(31, 83)
xs = temps - offset
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The following loop uses <c>xs</c> and the sample of parameters to construct an array
      of predicted probabilities.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
pred = np.empty((len(sample), len(xs)))

for i, (slope, inter) in enumerate(sample):
    pred[i] = expit(inter + slope * xs)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      To get a quick sense of what the predictions look like, we can loop through the rows
      and plot each one.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
for ps in pred:
    plt.plot(temps, ps, color='C1', lw=0.5, alpha=0.4)
    
plot_data(data)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      In each column, I'll compute the median to quantify the central tendency and a 90%
      credible interval.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
low, median, high = np.percentile(pred, [5, 50, 95], axis=0)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      The results are arrays containing predicted probabilities for the lower bound of the
      credible interval, the median, and the upper bound.
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
plt.fill_between(temps, low, high, color='C1', alpha=0.2)
plt.plot(temps, median, color='C1', label='logistic model')

plot_data(data)
      </input>
    </program>
    <p>
      According to these results, the probability of damage to the O-rings at various
      temperatures is:
    </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
low = pd.Series(low, temps)
median = pd.Series(median, temps)
high = pd.Series(high, temps)
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
t = 80
print(median[t], (low[t], high[t]))
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
t = 60
print(median[t], (low[t], high[t]))
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
t = 31
print(median[t], (low[t], high[t]))
      </input>
    </program>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch16-exercises">
    <title>Exercises</title>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch16-1">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose a political pundit claims to be able to predict the outcome of elections
          based on an algorithm that considers economic factors.
          Suppose we start with prior odds of 4:1 that the pundit's algorithm is legitimate.
        </p>
        <p>
          Compute the prior log odds.
        </p>
        <program language="python">
          <input>
# Solution goes here
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          Compute the log likelihood ratios for each of three election outcomes.
        </p>
        <program language="python">
          <input>
# Solution goes here
          </input>
        </program>
        <p>
          Compute the posterior log odds after three updates.
        </p>
        <program language="python">
          <input>
# Solution goes here
          </input>
        </program>
      </statement>
      <solution>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

prior_log_odds = np.log(4)
prior_log_odds
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

lr1 = np.log(7/5)
lr2 = np.log(3/5)
lr3 = np.log(9/5)

lr1, lr2, lr3
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

# In total, these three outcomes provide evidence that the
# pundit's algorithm is legitmate, although with K=1.8,
# it is weak evidence.

posterior_log_odds = prior_log_odds + lr1 + lr2 + lr3
posterior_log_odds
      </input>
    </program>
      </solution>
    </exercise>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-ch16-2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          An article in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> reports results suggesting
          that children born just after the cutoff date for school enrollment are more likely
          to be diagnosed with ADHD than children born just before the cutoff date.
          The article suggests that this difference is due to the relative age effect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here are the number of children born in each month and the number diagnosed with ADHD.
        </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
n = np.array([32690, 31238, 34405, 34565, 34977, 34415, 
                   36577, 36319, 35353, 34405, 31285, 31617])

k = np.array([265, 280, 307, 312, 317, 287, 
                      320, 309, 225, 240, 232, 243])
      </input>
    </program>
        <p>
          I'm going to "roll" the data so it starts in September rather than January.
        </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
x = np.arange(12)
n = np.roll(n, -8)
k = np.roll(k, -8)
      </input>
    </program>
        <p>
          And I'll put it in a <c>DataFrame</c> with one row for each month and the diagnosis rate.
        </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
adhd = pd.DataFrame(dict(x=x, k=k, n=n))
adhd['rate'] = adhd['k'] / adhd['n'] * 10000
adhd
      </input>
    </program>
        <p>
          Here's what the diagnosis rates look like.
        </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
def plot_adhd(adhd):
    plt.plot(adhd['x'], adhd['rate'], 'o', 
             label='data', color='C0', alpha=0.4)
    
    plt.axvline(5.5, color='gray', alpha=0.2)
    plt.text(6, 64, 'Younger than average')
    plt.text(5, 64, 'Older than average', horizontalalignment='right')

    decorate(xlabel='Birth date, months after cutoff',
             ylabel='Diagnosis rate per 10,000')
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
plot_adhd(adhd)
      </input>
    </program>
        <p>
          For the first 9 months, from September to May, we see what we would expect if some
          children are misdiagnosed due to the relative age effect.
        </p>
        <p>
          Here are the prior distributions.
        </p>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
qs = np.linspace(-5.2, -4.6, num=51)
prior_inter = make_uniform(qs, 'Intercept')
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
qs = np.linspace(0.0, 0.08, num=51)
prior_slope = make_uniform(qs, 'Slope')
      </input>
    </program>
        <p>
          Make a joint prior distribution and update it using the data for the first nine months.
          Then update with the data for the last three months.
        </p>
        <program language="python">
          <input>
# Solution goes here
          </input>
        </program>
      </statement>
      <solution>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

joint = make_joint(prior_inter, prior_slope)
joint.head()
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

joint_pmf = Pmf(joint.stack())
joint_pmf.head()
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

num_legit = 9
adhd1 = adhd.loc[0:num_legit-1]
adhd2 = adhd.loc[num_legit:]
adhd1
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

adhd2
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

from scipy.stats import binom

likelihood1 = joint_pmf.copy()

xs = adhd1['x']
ks = adhd1['k']
ns = adhd1['n']

for slope, inter in joint_pmf.index:
    ps = expit(inter + slope * xs)
    likes = binom.pmf(ks, ns, ps)
    likelihood1[slope, inter] = likes.prod()

likelihood1.sum()
      </input>
    </program>
    <program language="python">
      <input>
# Solution

# This update uses the binomial survival function to compute
# the probability that the number of cases *exceeds* `ks`.

likelihood2 = joint_pmf.copy()

xs = adhd2['x']
ks = adhd2['k']
ns = adhd2['n']

for slope, inter in joint_pmf.index:
    ps = expit(inter + slope * xs)
    likes = binom.sf(ks, ns, ps)
    likelihood2[slope, inter] = likes.prod()

likelihood2.sum()
